   443	## 8. Validity: the closed change-source enumeration
   444	
   445	### 8.1 The table (I16: closed, audited by CI sweep against the schema)
   446	
   447	| # | change source | observer (stamp + conjunct) | killed schedule |
   448	|---|---|---|---|
   449	| S1 | write in slot s | `slotWriteSeq[s]`; record valid only if ∀s ∈ mask: wc[s] ≤ r.seq; fingerprint newest-visible term | C1 memo half, C5 |
   450	| S2 | retirement (fold/compaction) | `worldMemoEpoch` mint (R10, from globalSeq); `baseSeq` monotone max | judge-B1 compaction |
   451	| S2b | **visibility flip below the max** (retirement or lock-in exposes an OLDER entry) | **visStamp(a)** minted at retire-fold and per-root lock-in; term in fp's max | HC-F1/HX-2 (I21) |
   452	| S3 | evaluator identity | staged per pass, promoted at hook commit (I22); fnStamp/reducerStamp conjuncts; committed evaluator for NEWEST/committed/effect/fixup evals | HC-F2/HX-1/CX-1/LX-4 |
   453	| S4 | thenable settlement | generation-checked back-ref kill + pending-only belt + settle-time flush re-check for SUSPENSION effect snapshots | TKC-2, HC-N2 |
   454	| S5 | episode / renumber | epoch-in-worldKey; renumber rewrites persistent stamp columns; heap-held snapshots epoch-guarded (stale ⇒ treated as moved, safe direction); hard horizon throw | C13/I8 |
   455	| S6 | world identity | in the key: (mask, pin, root-lock variant, epoch) | S18 pinless kills |
   456	| S7 | node identity recycle | staging (S15) + GEN generation checks | S15 arena leak, LX-6 |
   457	
   458	`fingerprint(atom, w) = max(newest w-visible entry seq, baseSeq,
   459	reducerStamp, visStamp)` — over-invalidates on unrelated same-atom flips
   460	(one ladder re-fold; safe direction), never under-invalidates: every
   461	outcome-changing source has a row, and the rows' stamps all mint from
   462	globalSeq (I15).
   463	
   464	### 8.2 The ladder (memo revalidation, cheap-first)
   465	
   466	1. epoch equal? (int) — else dead.
   467	2. per-slot clocks: ∀s ∈ mask: wc[s] ≤ r.seq (≤31 int compares, usually
   468	   1–2) — pass ⇒ serve.
   469	3. else fingerprint re-check per recorded atom dep (tape-tail + 3 loads +
   470	   max each): all unmoved ⇒ re-stamp r.seq, serve (recompute avoided).
   471	4. else re-evaluate (record fresh edges/memo).
   472	
   473	## 9. Suspense
   474	
   475	### 9.1 `ctx.use(thenableOrFactory)` — positional, per-lineage
   476	
   477	Cache key `(node, lineageId, position)` (D11: lineage is per
   478	root × batch-set, stable across restarts/replays — passSerial re-fetches
   479	forever, mask keys drift, live-set ids churn; all three excluded by the
   480	key's definition). The **lazy form** `ctx.use(() => makeRequest())`
   481	invokes the factory only when no valid entry exists — a retry's cache hit
   482	fires no user side effect (R14). The eager form stays legal with the
   483	honest contract: identity stability guaranteed; the caller's own eager
   484	side effects are not suppressed. Per-world positional identity satisfies
   485	R2/C14 (same positional thenable per world across replays).
   486	
   487	### 9.2 Content validity: the flattened prefix
   488	
   489	Entry records `prefix = [(atomId, fp(atom, w)) in read order] ∪
   490	[(computedId, effectiveFnStamp)]` for all tracked reads before the
   491	position, child evaluations merged into parents (S5 flatten; O21 owns the
   492	length risk — fallback: whole-mask clock vector + visStamp sum, coarser,
   493	flagged non-default). Reuse iff pairwise equal; else drop positions ≥ p,
   494	store fresh (generation-bumped). Properties, each with its witness:
   495	**retry-stable** — purity ⇒ same reads; fps and fnStamps are
   496	receipt-line facts, indifferent to memo/worldKey/pass churn (HX-4's
   497	livelock dead); **content-sensitive** — an included write moves the
   498	newest-visible term (I20), a visibility flip moves visStamp (HC-F1-B
   499	dead), an evaluator swap moves fnStamp (CX-4 dead); **starvation-free** —
   500	unrelated retirements touch no prefix atom ⇒ no visStamp mint on them ⇒
   501	prefix stable (LC-F1/S20 excluded *by the mint sites' definition*: vS
   502	mints only at folds/lock-ins touching that atom). Settlement: eager
   503	generation-checked back-ref kills the sentinel memo; a pending-only belt
   504	sweep covers the race; effect snapshots holding SUSPENSION outcomes get a
   505	settle-time flush re-check (S4 row).
   506	
   507	## 10. Notification
   508	
   509	Per-write full-reach walk over K0∪K1 out-edges from the written atom, in
   510	the writer's synchronous stack (D5): watched node ⇒
   511	`setState(watcher)` — React assigns the writer's priority, batches,
   512	entangles, and applies its own loop limits (R7's React half). Per-
   513	(watcher, slot) dedup bits on the watcher record, set at delivery,
   514	cleared when the component renders (re-arm ⇒ C4's second batch and any
   515	post-render same-slot write re-deliver). Value-blind (D13): no equality
   516	check anywhere on the delivery path — S16/S17's suppression scars.
   517	Signal-effect subscribers are enqueued into their root's touched-effect
   518	queue (dedup per flush window); flush triggers drain it targeted,
   519	O(affected) (G-R). No pruning, no cross-walk marks. The specced fallback
   520	if SPK-N1's grid fails: per-slot-mark **delivery dedup** per render cycle
   521	(dedup, never a value cutoff — D13). Engine `batch()` defers core-effect
   522	flushing only (D10); no watcher grouping exists to preserve context
   523	across, and no implicit grouping exists anywhere (C6's second trap
   524	answered by absence).
   525	
   526	## 11. React bindings (`cosignal/react`, provider-free)
   527	
   528	Bridge is module-global + a root registry keyed by fork rootId (R9 full
   529	spanning scope — C11). Hooks: `useSignal`/`useAtom`/`useReducerAtom`
   530	subscribe a watcher record + `useState(version)`; reads route under the
   531	current binding (§6.1). `useComputed(fn, deps)` mounts a hook-owned node
   532	(staged until its commit effect — S15). `useSignalEffect` registers a
   533	committed-channel effect with a dep snapshot.
   534	
   535	### 11.1 Staged evaluator identity (I22)
   536	
   537	Per invocation: compare incoming deps against **this pass's staged entry,
   538	else the committed evaluator**; changed ⇒ stage {fn, deps, fnStamp:
   539	++globalSeq} in the pass frame (burned seqs on discard are unobservable);
   540	a same-pass render restart re-compares and re-stages (LX-4 ⇒ new stamp ⇒
   541	memo conjunct fails ⇒ re-eval). Pass evaluations of the node use its
   542	staged evaluator; NEWEST, committed-world, fixup, and effect evaluations
   543	use the committed one — an uncommitted closure is unreachable outside its
   544	pass **by construction**: the staged table is keyed by the pass frame and
   545	consulted only through it (base: no staged entry ⇒ committed everywhere;
   546	step: the only readers of the staged table are evaluations holding that
   547	pass's binding). Promotion at the hook's OWN commit effect — hook-grain,
   548	which runs iff its subtree committed, so a fallback-committing root pass
   549	publishes nothing for abandoned subtrees (LX-2 unrepresentable: there is
   550	no pass-grain publication site in the design). Reducer identity:
   551	constructor reducers immutable; hook reducers stage/promote identically
   552	(D16; differential at stable-reducer scope; dev-warn on swap with pending
   553	receipts).
   554	
   555	### 11.2 Mount/subscribe fixup (the render→subscribe gap; I18/I13)
   556	
   557	```
   558	r = touchedSlots(n)
   559	if r == 0 ∧ CT(n): return                              // invariant R fast-out
   560	for each LIVE WRITTEN token t with slot(t) ∈ r:        // deferred AND default (R8-fix/HX-6); reach-based, no equality filter (I13/S10)
   561	  fork.runInBatch(t, () => setState(W))
   562	v_now = evaluate(n, committed-for-root(r))             // write-rejecting world eval (R4)
   563	if !isEqual(v_now, v_rendered): setState(W)            // unconditional fallback (I18) — covers retire-in-window
   564	```
   565	
   566	Bound: |touched ∩ live| correctives + one committed eval per flagged
   567	mount; 0 for R-clean mounts (G-F). The corrective joins the batch's OWN
   568	lanes (a fresh startTransition would be a different lane → a separate
   569	commit → a torn window — C10's explicit why-not). Windows walked: token
   570	retires inside render→layout ⇒ the committed compare fires (the fold
   571	precedes layout by R11); write lands after a pass completed but before
   572	commit ⇒ the walk delivers, and for not-yet-registered watchers the
   573	layout fixup's runInBatch plus F4's obligation (further work scheduled
   574	for those lanes, never absorbed silently) covers it (C10-R).
   575	
   576	### 11.3 Reconcile backstop (retirement-fold invisibility)
   577	
   578	At retirement, for each watcher on a touched node: compare its
   579	last-rendered value against the new committed value before bumping —
   580	already-correct components see nothing (urgent-applied folds are value
   581	no-ops); divergent ones get an urgent pre-paint correction (I14's
   582	third trigger; with R11 this runs before that root's layout effects).
   583	
   584	### 11.4 Effects
   585	
   586	`useSignalEffect` (committed channel): runs post-commit; records snapshot
   587	[(atomId, fp(atom, committed-for-root))] (+ epoch). Re-run check at each
   588	flush trigger: any snapshot fp moved ⇒ re-run. Triggers (I14, all three):
   589	commits on the root (passive phase drains the root's touched-effect
   590	queue); retirements — including committed=false store-only batches (the
   591	fold moved committed state with no commit anywhere); settlement re-checks
   592	for SUSPENSION snapshots. visStamp makes visibility flips move snapshots
   593	(C16-B1). Core `effect()` (non-React): documented contract = observes
   594	NEWEST, flushed synchronously at write (or at `batch()` close / microtask
   595	per `configure`) — stated and walked in C16 step 4; this is the
   596	benchmark-integrability configuration (R13).
   597	
   598	### 11.5 StrictMode / replays
   599	
   600	Render-phase reads are pure (memoized world evals; K1 edge re-records
   601	dedup against the node's existing adjacency; staging + GEN make discarded
   602	mounts reclaimable — S15). Render-phase writes throw (guard first line).
   603	Double-mounted effects net to one subscription via R1's microtask-
   604	debounced observed-lifecycle (flap-proof). Per-world thenable identity is
   605	positional per lineage — stable across replays (F5). Staged evaluators
   606	re-stage idempotently by deps compare.
   607	
   608	### 11.6 SSR/hydration (R10)
   609	
   610	Serialized committed atom state loads into K0 at construction (DIRECT);
   611	bridge registration precedes or follows hydration render — either order
   612	is safe (no receipts exist pre-registration; hydration reads NEWEST).
   613	RSC/Flight out of scope v1.
   614	
   615	### 11.7 Tracing (R11)
   616	
   617	Inherited from the reference bar: lazily-loadable recorder (ring +
   618	lossless), causality queries, Graphviz renderers; untraced cost = one
   619	slot check per site, both builds, inside the donor budget (the
   620	architecture does not force changes; per R11 the reference design is
   621	reused).
   622	
   623	## 12. Async actions: F8 = carrier + parking, build-complete (X1)
   624	
   625	Duties separated (I26): **parking** (lifetime — F3 holds retirement until
   626	the action's returned thenable settles; React's own entangled-action
   627	machinery already observes settlement) and **identity** (which token a
   628	post-await write belongs to — only a continuation carrier can know;
   629	promise-patching is correctness-dead, S22, measured: `await` never calls
   630	a patched `.then`).
   631	
   632	### 12.1 The async transform (bundler twin-build; I30, measured)
   633	
   634	Ships as a first-party bundler plugin (vite/rollup/webpack/swc backends,
   635	one shared core, maintained in-repo with the fork). For **every** async
   636	function (declaration, expression, arrow, method — and async generators
   637	via the wrap-async-generator driver shape, covering `for await` and
   638	post-`yield` resumptions) in app code — and, recommended, in bundled
   639	node_modules — emit:
   640	
   641	- `nativeBody` — the original function, untouched semantics;
   642	- `genBody` — the standard async-to-generator lowering (Babel
   643	  `_asyncToGenerator` driver shape) plus four lines: capture
   644	  `t = currentToken` at generator instantiation (async-resource
   645	  creation); before each `gen.next(v)`/`gen.throw(e)`: push `t`;
   646	  `finally` restore the previous token — including on throw, so `catch`/
   647	  `finally` blocks and escaped rejections observe the action token and
   648	  the ambient restores to null afterward (74/74 matrix, I30);
   649	- `wrapper(...a) = currentToken === null && armedActions === 0
   650	  ? nativeBody.apply(this, a) : genBody.apply(this, a)` — one
   651	  monomorphic null-check dispatch per async call site; `this`,
   652	  `new.target`, `arguments`, `super`, name/length preserved per the
   653	  standard lowering rules.
   654	
   655	The driver runs **only while an action token is live** (armed). Measured
   656	(I30, provenance `research/experiments/spf8-continuation-carrier.md`,
   657	74/74 correctness incl. Promise.all with mixed native promises, timers,
   658	async generators, catch/finally restore, two interleaved actions with
   659	zero bleed): unarmed ≈0% (−1.6%..+0.6% across 23 paired processes, inside
   660	the ±1.5% noise floor of a 100%-promise-machinery worst case); armed
   661	+24–26% of promise-machinery time ≈ **+12 ns/await** — cheaper than
   662	Node's AsyncLocalStorage (+38%) on the same shape. Code size ≈2× async-fn
   663	body bytes (async fns only); a plugin mode scopes twinning to
   664	action-reachable code; unconditional twinning is the simple correct mode.
   665	The plugin also **injects the probe module** (§12.4) and stamps
   666	`__COSIGNAL_ASYNC_TRANSFORM__ = <protocol version>`.
   667	
   668	### 12.2 Runtime carrier semantics (unchanged from the champion)
   669	
   670	`fork.currentBatchToken()` consults the carrier first: non-null ⇒ the
   671	action's token (receipt classifies under it, **parked**); null ⇒ React's
   672	current event/update context (lazy mint, microtask backfill). Action
   673	scope: `startTransition(async fn)` mints/enters token T; the sync prefix
   674	runs under T; every continuation of compiled async code restores T
   675	(§12.1); `armedActions` increments at scope entry, decrements at
   676	settle/reject (ambient token null after — matrix-checked). Nested
   677	`startTransition` while an action pends entangles to the action token
   678	(≤31 structural, I10; when React multiplexes transitions onto one lane
   679	they are ONE batch and ONE token — parity by construction: tokens are
   680	per lane-batch, not per call). Two interleaved actions hold distinct
   681	tokens with zero bleed (matrix). Retirement parks until the returned
   682	thenable settles (F3); the watermark rule (§5.2) is what makes the
   683	parked token's post-await writes safe on roots that committed earlier
   684	prefixes (I25; walk C11-W). Carrier identity construction (why the token
   685	is present at every resumption): base — captured at instantiation while
   686	the scope runs; step — every resumption of a compiled async fn passes
   687	through its driver's push/finally-restore bracket, and every async
   688	resource *created* during a bracketed span captures the bracketed token;
   689	uncompiled resumptions are exactly the §12.5 boundary. ∎
   690	
   691	### 12.3 The feature-detect ladder (what ships, in order)
   692	
   693	1. **Platform AsyncContext** (TC39 Stage 4, ES2026 — shipped nowhere as
   694	   of 2026-07, I30): if `AsyncContext.Variable` exists and passes a
   695	   behavioral probe, the carrier is a native Variable; the twin build is
   696	   unnecessary (the plugin may still be installed; its dispatch collapses
   697	   to the native branch); §12.5's boundary vanishes (host-level context
   698	   flows through uncompiled code too).
   699	2. **Twin-build carrier** (the bridge, today's default): §12.1 transform
   700	   verified by the boot self-test (§12.4).
   701	3. **Explicit `configure({asyncActions: 'unsupported'})`**: the
   702	   async-action surface is disabled loudly — `startTransition` (ours)
   703	   whose callback returns a thenable **throws** with a clear message
   704	   (detectable at the point of rejection: the returned value is a
   705	   thenable and the mode is 'unsupported'). Legal compositions that
   706	   remain, each walked or trivially reducible: synchronous transitions
   707	   (C1–C11 unaffected), sync writes before the first await of an
   708	   un-scoped async flow (they classify by ambient context as ordinary
   709	   writes), and store-only sync transitions (C12 first half). This is
   710	   the preamble-sanctioned interface restriction; it never forbids
   711	   behavior the user doesn't control (async actions are user-authored).
   712	4. **Neither transform nor AsyncContext nor explicit opt-out** ⇒
   713	   `registerReactBridge()` **throws at boot** (§12.4). Never a silent
   714	   rung (I26/D15).
   715	
   716	### 12.4 The loud boot self-test (build verifier — the meaning shift I30)
   717	
   718	At `registerReactBridge()`: (a) ladder-detect AsyncContext (rung 1); else
   719	(b) look up the **plugin-injected probe** — an async probe function that
   720	lives in *app-built* code (injected by the plugin, so its presence proves
   721	the plugin ran over the app bundle; a library-shipped probe would only
   722	prove the library's own build) — and run it inside a synthetic action
   723	scope: the probe awaits a resolved promise and reports the observed
   724	carrier token; token ≠ probe scope's token ⇒ transform missing or
   725	misapplied ⇒ **throw** (with the support-matrix message and the plugin
   726	version stamp vs protocol version); no probe registered and no rung-3
   727	opt-out ⇒ same throw. One-time cost, ≤1 ms class (one await + microtask
   728	drain; G-A). The self-test verifies the *build*, not the host — I30's
   729	prerequisite relocation, stated: "the platform prerequisite becomes a
   730	build prerequisite."
   731	
   732	### 12.5 Mixed compiled/uncompiled boundary semantics (the honest edge)
   733	
   734	What exactly happens when **untransformed** third-party async code writes
   735	signals inside an action (rung 2 only; rung 1 has no boundary):
   736	
   737	- **Mechanics.** The vendor fn's internal `await` resumes via native
   738	  machinery — no driver, no push — so `currentToken` is null there. A
   739	  post-await `a.set(2)` in that frame classifies by ambient context: a
   740	  real (usually default-priority) token D. The write is **logged under D,
   741	  applied to K0, walked, and retires with D** — every invariant of §5–§10
   742	  holds for it, because D is an ordinary batch.
   743	- **The bound (documented misattribution bound).** The deviation is
   744	  *attribution only*: the write commits at D's retirement — possibly
   745	  **before the action settles** (C12's timing for that write is not met)
   746	  — and it does not ride the action's world (T's renders exclude it;
   747	  urgent renders include it sooner). It is byte-for-byte the behavior of
   748	  the same write issued from a plain `setTimeout` callback. **Never**: a
   749	  lost write (D2/I1 — it has a receipt), a torn frame (all folds/worlds
   750	  remain self-consistent; delivery walks run), a stuck world, or a
   751	  lifecycle leak. Blast radius = the semantics of that one write's batch
   752	  membership.
   753	- **Detection limits, stated.** At the write site, token-null-during-
   754	  pending-action is *indistinguishable* from a legitimate concurrent
   755	  event write (a click during a pending action is also token-null) — so
   756	  runtime rejection is impossible without false positives, and the design
   757	  does not throw (a throw would ban ordinary concurrent input — preamble
   758	  rule (c)). Instead: **dev warning** on any logged write with carrier
   759	  token null while ≥1 action token is parked — imprecise by construction
   760	  (over-warns on legitimate concurrent events; the message says so and
   761	  names the vendor-transform remedy), catching the residual class in
   762	  development (I30's rule). The whole-app-untransformed case never
   763	  reaches this edge: §12.4 threw at boot.
   764	- **Remedies, in order**: apply the plugin to node_modules (bundlers can;
   765	  recommended default), wrap the vendor call's post-await work in
   766	  `fork.runInBatch(actionToken, …)` at the boundary (manual, precise), or
   767	  wait for rung 1 (AsyncContext erases the class).
   768	- Walk: **C12-U** (§17).
   769	
   770	### 12.6 Support matrix (the shipped line)
   771	
   772	| host/build | async actions |
   773	|---|---|
   774	| AsyncContext host (future) | native carrier; no build requirement; no boundary class |
   775	| bundled app + cosignal transform (today) | full support; untransformed vendor async code writing signals post-await inside an action misattributes to its ambient batch — sound, dev-warned, bounded (§12.5) |
   776	| unbundled/untransformed (raw ESM dev server), no AsyncContext | `registerReactBridge()` fails loudly; opt-out rung 3 disables async actions loudly |
   777	
   778	Everything else in this section — parking, entanglement, retirement,
   779	watermark interaction — is the champion's §12 verbatim.
   780	
   781	## 13. Semantics pins (conformance-tested contracts)
   782	
   783	- **Fold purity (D14/I28)**: signal reads/writes inside `update(fn)`/
   784	  reducer folds throw in all builds, through `untracked` too. Legal
   785	  composition: read before dispatch.
   786	- **Reducer identity (D16)**: constructor reducers immutable; hook
   787	  reducers stage per pass, promote at the hook's commit effect;
   788	  differential vs `useReducer` at stable-reducer scope; dev-warn on swap
   789	  with pending receipts.
   790	- **`ctx.previous` (D16 three-way)**: NEWEST/RENDER_NEWEST = donor global
   791	  previous (documented, conformance-pinned; per-root divergence of the
   792	  committed seed is a stated contract, not a leak); world evals = prior
   793	  `M(node, worldKey).value` (pass/world-scoped); else R-guarded K0 seed,
   794	  else undefined.
   795	- **`ctx.use` forms (D16/R14)**: lazy factory = full caching contract;
   796	  eager thenable = identity stability only.
   797	- **Core `effect()` contract**: NEWEST, synchronous under the documented
   798	  benchmark configuration (R13); `useSignalEffect` = committed-for-root
   799	  only (C16).
   800	- **R8**: writes inside computeds tolerated when acyclic on NEWEST

