    10	  by-construction claims are an automatic reviewer blocker. (This rule exists
    11	  because the previous judgment accepted exactly such a claim and it was
    12	  false.)
    13	- Reviewers attack these cases first; judges re-walk them last. A case that
    14	  cannot be walked in a design is a blocker, not a TODO.
    15	- **Restricting the interface is a legitimate design move.** A design may
    16	  resolve a case by *forbidding the pattern at runtime* (a thrown error with
    17	  a clear message) when the pattern is avoidable user code — but it must
    18	  then (a) show the forbidden pattern is reliably *detectable* at the point
    19	  of rejection, (b) define which nearby compositions remain legal, and walk
    20	  those, and (c) never forbid ordinary React behavior the user doesn't
    21	  control (flushSync in an event, time-slicing yields, StrictMode replays,
    22	  a component mounting mid-transition — those must be handled, not banned).
    23	
    24	Notation: `T`,`k` = deferred (transition-like) batches; `U` = urgent batch;
    25	`D` = default-priority batch (urgent-classified, but renders asynchronously —
    26	it can be *excluded* from a sync render). "World of X" = the state a render
    27	for X must observe. All cases assume React-mode (bindings active).
    28	
    29	---
    30	
    31	## C1 — World-divergent dependency (the killer; family of 7)
    32	
    33	Setup: atoms `flag=false, a=0, b=0`; computed `c = flag ? a : b`; component W
    34	subscribed to `c`; canonical deps of `c` = {flag, b}.
    35	
    36	Schedule: deferred batch k: `flag.set(true)` → (k-world read of `c` may
    37	happen here, caching 0 via `a`) → same batch k: `a.set(1)`.
    38	
    39	Required: the k-world value of `c` becomes 1 (any k-world cache invalidated);
    40	W is re-rendered **in k's lane before k commits** (no torn commit where
    41	siblings show k's world and W shows stale); committed world still reads 0
    42	via `b`.
    43	
    44	The trap: `a` has **no canonical edge** to `c`. Any invalidation or
    45	notification derived only from canonical topology cannot reach `c`/W. Any
    46	cache-validity record that only captured "atoms with concurrency state at
    47	evaluation time" misses `a` (it acquires state *after* the evaluation).
    48	
    49	Variants that must also be walked: T2 write to committed-only dep `b` in k
    50	(no k-world change; over-invalidation ok, wrong value not); T3 shared dep
    51	flips back (`flag=false` in k); T4 urgent write to `b` (committed changes,
    52	k-world doesn't); T5 urgent write to `a` (k-world sees it — pending worlds
    53	include applied urgent state); T6 slot/world-id reuse hygiene after k
    54	retires; T7 two live batches render together, one suspends, one commits
    55	alone (multi-batch and single-batch views over the same nodes).
    56	
    57	## C2 — flushSync excludes a pending default batch (forces always-log)
    58	
    59	Setup: atom `a=0`, computed `c = a + 10`, components on both.
    60	
    61	Schedule: in one event: `a.set(1)` lands in default-priority batch D
    62	(urgent-classified, applied to canonical state if the design applies urgent
    63	writes); then `flushSync(setState)` renders **SyncLane only** — D excluded.
    64	
    65	Required: the flushSync render reads `a=0` AND `c=10`. Both. A design whose
    66	canonical value moved and whose downstream computed can be served from a
    67	canonical cache shows `c=11` next to `a=0` — torn frame.
    68	
    69	The trap: (a) skipping history for urgent writes makes the older world
    70	unreconstructible (this case is the proof that **every** write needs a
    71	receipt in React mode); (b) recording the receipt but not marking/knowing
    72	the *downstream cone* is world-sensitive leaves `c` on the canonical fast
    73	path.
    74	
    75	## C3 — Rebase parity (React's updater-queue arithmetic)
    76	
    77	Setup: `a=1`. Deferred T: `a.update(x=>x+1)`; then urgent U:
    78	`a.update(x=>x*2)`.
    79	
    80	Required, in order: urgent render (excludes T) shows 2; U commits (fold is a
    81	no-op vs canonical); T's render shows 4 (`(1+1)*2` — replay in write order);
    82	T commits → committed value 4. `useReducer` side-by-side test must match at
    83	every step. A design that applies-and-discards the urgent updater folds T to
    84	2 or 3 — wrong. A plain `set 5` after a pending `+1` must commit 5 (not 6).
