    91	any re-render/commit, a *different* deferred batch T2 writes `a`.
    92	
    93	Required: W is also scheduled in **T2's lane** (T2's render includes W). The
    94	trap: once-per-staleness notification dedup (marks that stop walks; an ARMED
    95	bit that re-arms only after the watcher re-runs) has no path from the second
    96	write to W in T2's lane.
    97	
    98	## C5 — Cutoff-suppressed first write, effective second write (same batch)
    99	
   100	Setup: `c` reads `a` but its value doesn't change when `a` goes 0→1 (e.g.
   101	`c = a*0 + b`); watcher on `c`.
   102	
   103	Schedule: batch k writes `a=1` (broadcast correctly suppressed — value equal);
   104	then k writes `b=7`.
   105	
   106	Required: the second write reaches the watcher (setState in k's lane) even
   107	though the region is already marked/stale and the first broadcast was
   108	suppressed. Cache-validity must not serve the first evaluation's value.
   109	
   110	## C6 — Lane attribution under grouped notification
   111	
   112	Schedule: `batch(() => { a.set(1); startTransition(() => b.set(2)) })` — the
   113	engine-level batch closes *after* the transition scope ends.
   114	
   115	Required — one of two resolutions, stated explicitly:
   116	
   117	- **Handle it**: watcher setStates for `b`'s cone are assigned to the
   118	  transition's lanes (its render includes them; one commit carries them);
   119	  `a`'s cone gets urgent scheduling. Name the mechanism that preserves each
